</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3776556ED2B384FFF78F817FBE5F84F" pageId="634" pageNumber="635" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BD236DDED2B384FFF78F817FADFFB24" blockId="634.[136,778,1771,2070]" lastBlockId="634.[810,1452,853,2070]" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">
<emphasis id="B919EACFED2B384FFF78F817FE1CF832" bold="true" box="[189,473,2009,2035]" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">Description of female</emphasis>
. Body (
<figureCitation id="13562A58ED2B384FFD95F814FCC4F835" box="[592,769,2010,2036]" captionStart="FIGURE 429" captionStartId="633.[136,245,1907,1933]" captionTargetBox="[231,1339,214,1827]" captionTargetId="figure-18@633.[194,1392,185,1870]" captionTargetPageId="633" captionText="FIGURE 429. Nodoscarus curvus gen. et sp. nov., female. A, habitus of young adult, left; B, habitus of ovigerous adult, right; C, anterior region of body, dorsal; D, cephalosomal region, ventral; E, posterior end of body, dorsal; F, posterior end of body, ventral; G, antennule; H, antenna. Scale bars: A, B, 0.5 mm; C, E, F, 0.1 mm; D, 0.05 mm; G, H, 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4592178" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4592178/files/figure.png" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">Fig. 429A, B</figureCitation>
) vermiform, cylindrical, unsegmented, curved, densely covered with numerous minute setules (setules not shown in 
<figureCitation id="13562A58ED2B384FFC8BFCB9FC70FC50" box="[846,949,887,913]" captionStart="FIGURE 429" captionStartId="633.[136,245,1907,1933]" captionTargetBox="[231,1339,214,1827]" captionTargetId="figure-18@633.[194,1392,185,1870]" captionTargetPageId="633" captionText="FIGURE 429. Nodoscarus curvus gen. et sp. nov., female. A, habitus of young adult, left; B, habitus of ovigerous adult, right; C, anterior region of body, dorsal; D, cephalosomal region, ventral; E, posterior end of body, dorsal; F, posterior end of body, ventral; G, antennule; H, antenna. Scale bars: A, B, 0.5 mm; C, E, F, 0.1 mm; D, 0.05 mm; G, H, 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4592178" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4592178/files/figure.png" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">Fig. 429</figureCitation>
A-C). Bodylength 3.64 mm; body width 0.51 mm at widest region in middle, slightly narrowing in anterior and posterior quarters. Cephalosome poorly defined from metasome (
<figureCitation id="13562A58ED2B384FFBACFC13FB2FFC36" box="[1129,1258,989,1015]" captionStart="FIGURE 429" captionStartId="633.[136,245,1907,1933]" captionTargetBox="[231,1339,214,1827]" captionTargetId="figure-18@633.[194,1392,185,1870]" captionTargetPageId="633" captionText="FIGURE 429. Nodoscarus curvus gen. et sp. nov., female. A, habitus of young adult, left; B, habitus of ovigerous adult, right; C, anterior region of body, dorsal; D, cephalosomal region, ventral; E, posterior end of body, dorsal; F, posterior end of body, ventral; G, antennule; H, antenna. Scale bars: A, B, 0.5 mm; C, E, F, 0.1 mm; D, 0.05 mm; G, H, 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4592178" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4592178/files/figure.png" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">Fig. 429C</figureCitation>
), with rounded anterior margin. Posterior part of body bearing horizontal sclerotization bar and weak cleft (as vestige of articulation between metasome and urosome) on dorsal surface (
<figureCitation id="13562A58ED2B384FFABBFB8DFCACFBBE" captionStart="FIGURE 429" captionStartId="633.[136,245,1907,1933]" captionTargetBox="[231,1339,214,1827]" captionTargetId="figure-18@633.[194,1392,185,1870]" captionTargetPageId="633" captionText="FIGURE 429. Nodoscarus curvus gen. et sp. nov., female. A, habitus of young adult, left; B, habitus of ovigerous adult, right; C, anterior region of body, dorsal; D, cephalosomal region, ventral; E, posterior end of body, dorsal; F, posterior end of body, ventral; G, antennule; H, antenna. Scale bars: A, B, 0.5 mm; C, E, F, 0.1 mm; D, 0.05 mm; G, H, 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4592178" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4592178/files/figure.png" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">Fig. 429E</figureCitation>
), copulatory pore on ventral surface (
<figureCitation id="13562A58ED2B384FFAEDFBABFA5AFBBE" box="[1320,1439,1125,1151]" captionStart="FIGURE 429" captionStartId="633.[136,245,1907,1933]" captionTargetBox="[231,1339,214,1827]" captionTargetId="figure-18@633.[194,1392,185,1870]" captionTargetPageId="633" captionText="FIGURE 429. Nodoscarus curvus gen. et sp. nov., female. A, habitus of young adult, left; B, habitus of ovigerous adult, right; C, anterior region of body, dorsal; D, cephalosomal region, ventral; E, posterior end of body, dorsal; F, posterior end of body, ventral; G, antennule; H, antenna. Scale bars: A, B, 0.5 mm; C, E, F, 0.1 mm; D, 0.05 mm; G, H, 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4592178" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4592178/files/figure.png" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">Fig. 429F</figureCitation>
), and shallow posteromedian incision. Caudal rami absent (fully incorporated into posterior margin of abdomen), but 1 small caudal seta present on each side.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD236DDED2B384FFC9AFB20FBFFF9F8" blockId="634.[810,1452,853,2070]" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">
Rostrum (
<figureCitation id="13562A58ED2B384FFC0BFB23FB84FAC6" box="[974,1089,1261,1287]" captionStart="FIGURE 429" captionStartId="633.[136,245,1907,1933]" captionTargetBox="[231,1339,214,1827]" captionTargetId="figure-18@633.[194,1392,185,1870]" captionTargetPageId="633" captionText="FIGURE 429. Nodoscarus curvus gen. et sp. nov., female. A, habitus of young adult, left; B, habitus of ovigerous adult, right; C, anterior region of body, dorsal; D, cephalosomal region, ventral; E, posterior end of body, dorsal; F, posterior end of body, ventral; G, antennule; H, antenna. Scale bars: A, B, 0.5 mm; C, E, F, 0.1 mm; D, 0.05 mm; G, H, 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4592178" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4592178/files/figure.png" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">Fig. 429D</figureCitation>
) large, longerthanwide, weakly tapering towards rounded apex; surface covered with numerous setules. Antennule (
<figureCitation id="13562A58ED2B384FFBBCFAFFFB29FA8A" box="[1145,1260,1329,1355]" captionStart="FIGURE 429" captionStartId="633.[136,245,1907,1933]" captionTargetBox="[231,1339,214,1827]" captionTargetId="figure-18@633.[194,1392,185,1870]" captionTargetPageId="633" captionText="FIGURE 429. Nodoscarus curvus gen. et sp. nov., female. A, habitus of young adult, left; B, habitus of ovigerous adult, right; C, anterior region of body, dorsal; D, cephalosomal region, ventral; E, posterior end of body, dorsal; F, posterior end of body, ventral; G, antennule; H, antenna. Scale bars: A, B, 0.5 mm; C, E, F, 0.1 mm; D, 0.05 mm; G, H, 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4592178" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4592178/files/figure.png" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">Fig. 429G</figureCitation>
) as unsegmented lobe, much wider than long, densely setulose on ventral surface, armed with about 20 small setae. Antenna (
<figureCitation id="13562A58ED2B384FFABBFABBFCACFA73" captionStart="FIGURE 429" captionStartId="633.[136,245,1907,1933]" captionTargetBox="[231,1339,214,1827]" captionTargetId="figure-18@633.[194,1392,185,1870]" captionTargetPageId="633" captionText="FIGURE 429. Nodoscarus curvus gen. et sp. nov., female. A, habitus of young adult, left; B, habitus of ovigerous adult, right; C, anterior region of body, dorsal; D, cephalosomal region, ventral; E, posterior end of body, dorsal; F, posterior end of body, ventral; G, antennule; H, antenna. Scale bars: A, B, 0.5 mm; C, E, F, 0.1 mm; D, 0.05 mm; G, H, 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4592178" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4592178/files/figure.png" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">Fig. 429H</figureCitation>
) stout, 3-segmented; coxa and basis unarmed; endopod distinctly shorter than basis, about 1.8 times longerthanwide (44×25 μm); armedwith 6 smallsetae (arranged as 2, 2, and 2) plus stout terminal claw, about half as long as endopod.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD236DDED2B384FFC9AF98FFB7FF8AD" blockId="634.[810,1452,853,2070]" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">
Labrum (
<figureCitation id="13562A58ED2B384FFC08F98FFB8DF99D" box="[973,1096,1601,1628]" captionStart="FIGURE 429" captionStartId="633.[136,245,1907,1933]" captionTargetBox="[231,1339,214,1827]" captionTargetId="figure-18@633.[194,1392,185,1870]" captionTargetPageId="633" captionText="FIGURE 429. Nodoscarus curvus gen. et sp. nov., female. A, habitus of young adult, left; B, habitus of ovigerous adult, right; C, anterior region of body, dorsal; D, cephalosomal region, ventral; E, posterior end of body, dorsal; F, posterior end of body, ventral; G, antennule; H, antenna. Scale bars: A, B, 0.5 mm; C, E, F, 0.1 mm; D, 0.05 mm; G, H, 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4592178" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4592178/files/figure.png" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">Fig. 429D</figureCitation>
) broad with convex posterior margin. Mandible (
<figureCitation id="13562A58ED2B384FFBC4F9ADFBB0F9BF" box="[1025,1141,1635,1662]" captionStart="FIGURE 430" captionStartId="634.[136,245,717,743]" captionTargetBox="[159,1431,224,654]" captionTargetId="figure-19@634.[136,1451,199,668]" captionTargetPageId="634" captionText="FIGURE 430. Nodoscarus curvus gen. et sp. nov., female. A, mandible; B, maxillule; C, maxilla. Scale bars: 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4592180" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4592180/files/figure.png" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">Fig. 430A</figureCitation>
) represented only by lobate palp bearing 7 setae distally (4 on outer side and 3 on slightly projecting inner side). Maxillule (
<figureCitation id="13562A58ED2B384FFAC8F969FA46F903" box="[1293,1411,1703,1730]" captionStart="FIGURE 430" captionStartId="634.[136,245,717,743]" captionTargetBox="[159,1431,224,654]" captionTargetId="figure-19@634.[136,1451,199,668]" captionTargetPageId="634" captionText="FIGURE 430. Nodoscarus curvus gen. et sp. nov., female. A, mandible; B, maxillule; C, maxilla. Scale bars: 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4592180" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4592180/files/figure.png" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">Fig. 430B</figureCitation>
) as lobe bearing 9 setae (3 on medial margin smaller than others). Maxilla (
<figureCitation id="13562A58ED2B384FFC29F925FB9BF8C7" box="[1004,1118,1771,1798]" captionStart="FIGURE 430" captionStartId="634.[136,245,717,743]" captionTargetBox="[159,1431,224,654]" captionTargetId="figure-19@634.[136,1451,199,668]" captionTargetPageId="634" captionText="FIGURE 430. Nodoscarus curvus gen. et sp. nov., female. A, mandible; B, maxillule; C, maxilla. Scale bars: 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4592180" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4592180/files/figure.png" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">Fig. 430C</figureCitation>
) distinctly 3-segmented, with 2, 1, and 4 setae on first to third segments, respectively; setae on first segment weakly pinnate, remaining setae naked. Maxillipeds and legs absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD236DDED2B384FFC9AF8BAFBE5F84F" blockId="634.[810,1452,853,2070]" box="[863,1056,1908,1934]" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">
<emphasis id="B919EACFED2B384FFC9AF8BAFC59F84F" bold="true" box="[863,924,1908,1934]" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">Male</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3776556ED2B384EFC9AF858FDF0FEEC" lastPageId="635" lastPageNumber="636" pageId="634" pageNumber="635" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BD236DDED2B384EFC9AF858FDF0FEEC" blockId="634.[810,1452,853,2070]" lastBlockId="635.[136,778,173,301]" lastPageId="635" lastPageNumber="636" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">
<emphasis id="B919EACFED2B384FFC9AF858FC09F871" bold="true" box="[863,972,1942,1968]" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">Remarks</emphasis>
. Three characteristic features of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EED2B384FFAFAF858FA69F86E" authority="Kim &amp; Boxshall, 2020" authorityName="Kim &amp; Boxshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[1343,1452,1942,1968]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Nodoscarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="634" pageNumber="635" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvus" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B919EACFED2B384FFAFAF858FA97F86E" box="[1343,1362,1942,1967]" italics="true" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">N</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B919EACFED2B384FFAA4F858FA69F86E" box="[1377,1452,1942,1967]" italics="true" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">curvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B919EACFED2B384FFCEFF876FC16F813" bold="true" box="[810,979,1976,2002]" pageId="634" pageNumber="635">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A22A57B4ED2B384FFCEFF876FC16F813" box="[810,979,1976,2002]" pageId="634" pageNumber="635" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
serve to differentiate itfrom its congeners: (1) the mandibular palp is armed with 7 setae; (2) the maxilla is distinctly 3-segmented and (3) is armed with 2, 1, and 4 setae on first to third segments, respectively. The presence of a single small caudal seta on the tip of the paired posteriorabdominal lobes seems to be an additional differential feature of the new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
